  "market_context": "After midnight open and London session, ES and NQ are compared on the 1-hour. ES has pushed up to a higher high while NQ has not, forming an SMT divergence near the London high. Sell-side liquidity rests below around 4796 on ES and 16940 on NQ.",
  "key_observation": "The SMT remains valid only while NQ fails to take its corresponding high. If NQ trades through that high the divergence is invalidated; if a bullish PD array is then formed and not respected, price is likely to continue lower toward sell-side liquidity.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Mark the London high on both ES and NQ on the 1-hour chart as the reference liquidity level.",
    "Step 2: Observe that ES has taken its London high while NQ has not, drawing the SMT divergence trendline between the two highs.",
    "Step 3: Note that SMT alone is not a trigger — wait for structure and a PD array reaction to align before considering shorts.",
    "Step 4: Watch whether NQ takes its high; if it does, the SMT is invalidated, so monitor closely as price approaches that level.",
    "Step 5: NQ does not take the high, preserving the SMT. A bullish PD array then forms — test whether it is respected.",
    "Step 6: The bullish PD array is not respected and price breaks down, confirming the SMT as a reversal confluence.",
    "Step 7: Anticipate continuation lower toward sell-side liquidity (≈4796 on ES, ≈16940 on NQ) and see price reach those lows."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price rejected the bullish PD array and expanded lower, sweeping sell-side liquidity on both ES and NQ as anticipated.",
  "lessons": "SMT is a confluence, not a standalone trigger. It must be validated by NQ failing to take its corresponding high, and confirmed by structure such as a bullish PD array failing to hold before shorting toward sell-side liquidity.",
